T1  - New evidence on the small properties of estimators of sur models with autocorrelated disturbances
AU  - Maeshiro, Asatoshi
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 12
IS  - 2
SP  - 177
EP  - 187
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/02/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(80)90005-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407680900056
AB  - This study analytically examines the effect of trends in exogenous variables on the small-sample relative performance of alternative estimators of a SUR model with positively autocorrelated AR(1) disturbances. It is disclosed that when exogenous variables are trended: (1) an estimator that makes both autocorrelation and cross-correlation adjustments of the disturbances but drops the first observations in the process of autocorrelation adjustment frequently performs worse than OLS; (2) an estimator that makes cross-correlation adjustment ignoring the autocorrelation of the disturbances can occasionally be less efficient than OLS. The implied prescription for a practicing econometrician is, then, that he should use an estimator that makes a complete adjustment of both correlations, i.e., a GLS version.
ER  - 

